# Milestone and Epic Structure

Use this rule when organizing roadmap or project board structure.

## Core Rule

Milestones and epics should reflect delivery outcomes, not vague buckets of activity.

## Milestones Should Represent (GymVoice)

- **M1 — Foundation** — Repo, workflow, baseline docs, project setup (mobile + backend), CI; project ready for feature work.
- **M2 — Auth and first vertical slice** — Auth (OAuth or custom); voice-to-text; ParseExerciseSkill; minimal session/set persistence; speak → confirm → persist one set.
- **M3 — Voice pipeline and session** — VoiceParserAgent, ErrorHandlerAgent, GroupSeriesSkill, SessionManager; session start/end; set and set-group persistence; confirm/clarify flow.
- **M4 — History, progress, and polish** — History view (day/week/month); progress and trends; Spanish UI; error handling and UX polish; unit/integration/UI tests; MVP complete.
- **M5+ — Post-MVP** — Richer progress visualization, offline support, new skills; scope defined when M4 is complete.

See `docs/planning/MILESTONES.md` and `docs/planning/MVP_PLAN.md` for the single source of truth.

## Epics or Themes Can Represent

Larger functional areas such as:

- auth
- session lifecycle
- voice pipeline (parsing, grouping)
- set and set-group persistence
- history and progress
- error handling and confirmation flow
- UI (screens, Spanish copy)

## Avoid

Avoid milestone or epic names that are:

- too vague (“Phase 2,” “Improvements”)
- too broad (“Complete the app”)
- purely organizational with no delivery meaning
- mixtures of unrelated technical and product work

## Final Rule

A milestone or epic should help people understand what meaningful capability is being delivered. Align issues with milestone outcomes and dependencies.
